$segment3/604 // Buck: So, let's talk about the history of Redwood Research.
$segment3/605 // Buck: I'll I'll let you ask the questions at the starting start at least the start of the story.
$segment3/606 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/607 // Ryan: So, you wanna talk about, maybe the, like, first, Redwood Research pub project that ended up getting published Mhmm.
$segment3/608 // Ryan: And what the history of that was like and who was working at Redwood at the time?
$segment3/609 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment3/610 // Buck: So I guess, like, one thing is Redwood Research started growing out of another project that me and some other people had been doing.
$segment3/611 // Buck: And so we basically decided to stop doing that other thing and start working on empirical AI safety research or AI alignment research as we called it at the time.
$segment3/612 // Buck: And this happened in, like, mid twenty twenty one.
$segment3/613 // Buck: And we decided that the first empirical AI safety project we were gonna do was this adversarial robustness paper where it it it's kind of bizarrely similar to, research that's happened recently on, classifiers to detect whether LLMs have been jailbreak jailbroken or are answering questions that they that they shouldn't.
$segment3/614 // Buck: But at the time, we weren't really used to LMs as chatbots yet.
$segment3/615 // Buck: This was, you know, mid twenty twenty one, so, like, a year before ChatGPT and even before Claude was was out.
$segment3/616 // Ryan: And to be clear, at the time, you were imagining that you'd be using LMs as like a policy generating actions, this sort of thing.
$segment3/617 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment3/618 // Buck: We were totally imagining that.
$segment3/619 // Buck: I don't I wish that I had more data on exactly what we were imagining when.
$segment3/620 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment3/621 // Buck: But definitely definitely something like that.
$segment3/622 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment3/623 // Buck: So we decided to do this project where we would, try to make a classifier that was really robust, and really able to prevent the AI from doing a bad thing without us detecting it.
$segment3/624 // Buck: So in particular, we decided to focus on the definition of when given a, input that is some, you know, a fraction of some, like, snippet of fan fiction, it should never continue that in a way that is plausibly describing an injury.
$segment3/625 // Buck: This was covered, in my opinion, hilariously on Astral Card X 10.
$segment3/626 // Buck: So people who wanna learn more about this project can can read that version there.
$segment3/627 // Buck: But So so we did that project.
$segment3/628 // Buck: Initially, it was all of us at Redwood Research, which was something like maybe six and then increasingly many full time technical staff for the first six months, and then it went down to only being four people for the duration of the project.
$segment3/629 // Buck: And then eventually, it got submitted to a conference and made it in, I think, to NeurIPS.
$segment3/630 // Buck: Overall, I think that the project I think this project went, like, kind of surprisingly badly.
$segment3/631 // Buck: I think we in hindsight, I think one thing is it's been quite unimpactful.
$segment3/632 // Buck: I think that even though the work we were doing there is in some ways quite foresightful, it was, you know, hiring humans and trying to, do this iterative red team blue team game where we try to jailbreak our model, and try to or try to trick the model.
$segment3/633 // Buck: We didn't think of it as jailbreaking at the time.
$segment3/634 // Buck: And and then try to make our classifier more robust.
$segment3/635 // Buck: We I think that the techniques we developed there haven't been that influential.
$segment3/636 // Buck: I checked with Ethan Perez about whether our paper was helpful for the constitutional classifier work, he hopefully noted that it was not like, wasn't very influential on them.
$segment3/637 // Buck: Sir, I don't know.
$segment3/638 // Buck: I think there's a bunch of things that we did wrong there.
$segment3/639 // Buck: I think the first one is that we like, on the object level, I think we should have tried to publish something sooner and had lower a lower bar for success.
$segment3/640 // Buck: I think we had a lot of conceptual confusions.
$segment3/641 // Buck: On a more meta level, I kind of wish that we had assumed that we were gonna kind of suck at the first ML paper that we tried to write in this genre, and then had kind of an attitude of we wanna make it so that even if we make a bunch of terrible choices about how to write this paper, it isn't gonna be too costly for us and and we can like learn and move on as quickly as possible.
$segment3/642 // Buck: Like, wish that we had started out by saying, well, probably we're gonna suck at the first project we do in this genre.
$segment3/643 // Buck: So we should try to do a project where we really don't care if we suck because it was so short.
$segment3/644 // Buck: Like, I wish that we'd started out by trying to do a, like, one month long project, which had a tangible output.
$segment3/645 // Buck: And then I think we would have learned something from following the whole process and would have been able to do more stuff from there.
$segment3/646 // Buck: I think another related error is I think that we should have tried to focus on doing small projects more than big projects in general.
$segment3/647 // Buck: Like, I think at the time, there was so little work that was happening on AI safety that there were lots of pieces of low hanging fruit that we could have tried to tackle, especially with the skill sets of the people we had around.
$segment3/648 // Buck: And I think we should have tried to just, I think we should have been more in the business of looking for incredibly small things that were still like bite sized contributions and and trying to put those out quickly so that we could iterate on our process more.
$segment3/649 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/650 // Ryan: So I know there was, like, some response where the paper initially came out, and then you read it or DMZ regretted, who DMZ is one of the people working on the project, how it was presented.
