$segment3/718 // Ryan: Like, how much of the theory of change there was making it so people who were going to work on, like, AI safety adjacent stuff are better at machine learning versus making it so that people who are somewhat interested in AI safety adjacent stuff actually end up doing AI safety adjacent stuff while also incidentally making them machine learning.
$segment3/719 // Buck: I would say it's, like, maybe 70% motivated by causing people who were already pretty interested in doing AI safety stuff to have a better chance of getting jobs doing it and to do a better job of those jobs as opposed to getting people who weren't likely to do it, to be more interested in this stuff.
$segment3/720 // Buck: Though there was one person who was a, like, you know, a I think he was like a quant trading savant or whatever who was working at some famous quant trading firm, and he was very young and he hadn't had very much, contact with the AI safety community before.
$segment3/721 // Buck: And he showed up and he was like, you know, frankly, it's very unlikely that I'm gonna wanna work on AI safety stuff after this because I would have to turn down my, you know, very high salary that I'm I'm getting in my trading jobs or whatever.
