$segment3/728 // Ryan: And then moving on from MLAB, you were talking about a phase where Redwood was moving into doing interpretability research?
$segment3/729 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment3/730 // Buck: So we decided to do a lot of interpretability research.
$segment3/731 // Buck: So the people at Anthropic had very kindly shared us with a bunch of their, shared us on a bunch of their, unpublished interpretability work, the stuff that eventually was written up into a mathematical framework for transformer circuits.
$segment3/732 // Buck: So this was Chris Ola and his collaborators at Anthropic at the time.
$segment3/733 // Buck: And then we decided that we should do a bunch of work in that field.
$segment3/734 // Buck: I think one motivation for this was like kind of table stakes is that it seemed like a pretty promising research direction.
$segment3/735 // Buck: And then I think I wanted to do work on it in particular because of the fact that I thought it played to my strengths as a researcher.
$segment3/736 // Buck: Specifically, I'm a guy who is pretty mathy and pretty, like, strong at thinking about conceptual stuff, this is at least what I thought at the time, and I like someone standby compared to a bunch of other people in AI safety.
$segment3/737 // Buck: I just felt like I'm, like, more able to invent mathematical concepts and, like, come up with experiments and, like, think through stuff than I thought a lot of other people were.
$segment3/738 // Buck: And so we decided we were gonna do a bunch of, interpretability stuff.
$segment3/739 // Buck: And Paul Christianer, who we were talking to a lot of the time, thought this was a pretty reasonable idea and had some initial ideas for research directions, and we decided we were gonna do that.
$segment3/740 // Buck: And in hindsight, the part of this that I most regret or, like, the way that that decision procedure seems like most messed up is I feel like we were focused on a random aspect of mine, which is that I'm kind of thoughtful about doing math and making up math concepts.
$segment3/741 // Buck: But in fact, I think that, being thoughtful about doing math and making up math concepts is, like, absolutely not the most relevant skill set for producing value via doing research vaguely along the lines of mechanistic interpretability.
$segment3/742 // Buck: I think I think that this yeah.
$segment3/743 // Buck: It's just like not really had good consequences.
$segment3/744 // Buck: I think that we should have approached it if we were gonna do stuff about model internals.
$segment3/745 // Buck: I think we should have approached it in a much more breadth first manner where we name projects starting from, like, low complexity to, like, high complexity.
$segment3/746 // Buck: We're like, what are the things where it's craziest that no one has ever run a basic experiment on this before that would tell us something, anything that's kind of interesting about how neural networks work?
$segment3/747 // Buck: And we can try and do those in increasing order of complexity.
$segment3/748 // Buck: And I think that that would have been better than the actual kind of more, end to end focus that we were using.
$segment3/749 // Buck: The other way in which I think it was a mistake to focus on that stuff is I think a lot of what I'm really interested in and then what you're really interested in is thinking about AI futurism and trying to direct our research based on this kind of back chained end to end story about what needs to happen in order for AI to go well.
$segment3/750 // Buck: And unfortunately, research, which is like a real shot on goal or like a real moonshot, I think kind of works particularly poorly in combination with thinking about futurism.
$segment3/751 // Buck: Like, the thing about interpretability is like, we're like, well, obviously, if we were extremely good at interpretability, we wouldn't have any of these other problems.
$segment3/752 // Buck: Like, the alignment strategy would be like, well, you use your extremely good interpretability to check if the AI is plotting against you.
$segment3/753 // Buck: And if the AI is plotting against you, you don't deploy it or, like, you use your really good interpretability to change it into an AI that loves you and wants only the best for you.
$segment3/754 // Buck: And so there's kind of a way where, like, thinking about interpretability, the obvious way to do a good job of interpretability research, at least ambitious interpretability research, is to shoot for a situation where you don't have a bunch of messy trade offs as a result of having limited resources.
$segment3/755 // Buck: But, actually, I think we really like and are really good at thinking about what you should do when you have messy trade offs, when you have very limited resources, when an AI company is behaving recklessly and going fast.
$segment3/756 // Buck: And the interpretability research, because of how ambitious it is, doesn't really give us an opportunity to use that skill set.
$segment3/757 // Buck: And I don't know what we were thinking at the time.
$segment3/758 // Buck: Like, I I think I just, like, hadn't quite understood the the strength that we should be leaning into as an organization is, thinking through futurism and thinking through, like, what the good things to do on the margin for AI safety are or, like like, nowadays, I think we really focus on what are things that are, like, fairly easy and seem pretty doable, but might might not get done.
$segment3/759 // Buck: And I think that we should have focused more on that at the time as well.
$segment3/760 // Buck: It's a little confusing because even at the time, I was very interested in understanding what marginal improvements would be.
$segment3/761 // Buck: Like, I was giving talks in 2021 where I talked about the current plan for AI alignment, where I often mentioned, you know, here's what we would do at the moment, and here are ways we could try to improve that on the margin.
$segment3/762 // Buck: But I then didn't think to focus my research on things that are inspired by what would be good on the margin, and I I regret that.
$segment3/763 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/764 // Ryan: I mean, from my perspective, I feel like a lot of the mistakes that we made during the time when we were working on interpretability really came down to just generically not being very good researchers or something.
$segment3/765 // Ryan: Like, when I think about my mistakes, it feels like a lot of them are just addressed by just, like, bad heuristics about how to direct research.
$segment3/766 // Ryan: Not necessarily, like, bad taste in terms of what's exciting to pursue, but bad taste about, like, how to, like, prioritize pursuing it in a way that's, like, not very easy to, like like, I I don't think it was a thing where, like, if only we had read the blog post on how to do research correctly by mister researcher band or whatever, we would have known.
$segment3/767 // Ryan: It was more like just like heuristics about, like, what types of things seem like they often work and, like, when to give up on things and, like, how to, like, produce MVPs in ways that I think yeah.
$segment3/768 // Ryan: I I think we, like, made mistakes about this.
$segment3/769 // Ryan: And I I also I'm not super I feel like it is pretty good to lean into, like, really ambitious research in some senses.
$segment3/770 // Ryan: And I do wonder if now Redwood has overcorrected and we're insufficiently being trying to shoot for, like, ambitious research that would be very obviously extremely impactful if it succeeded.
$segment3/771 // Ryan: And we're instead doing research where the theory of change is complicated, but it feels pretty doable to keep pushing.
$segment3/772 // Ryan: And and I think that's just generally, like, a concern I have is, like, the safety community overall is under under invested in, like, very different ambitious bets.
$segment3/773 // Ryan: And instead, there's, like, a small number of ambitious bets that have people been working on for a long time where it's not obvious that the marginal labor is making much of a difference, and simultaneously, a bunch of very low ambition things where they seem like reasonable or they they might seem reasonable, but they're not like feel like I'm like I don't know.
$segment3/774 // Ryan: Like, one story is, like, research is very heavy tailed.
$segment3/775 // Ryan: Some of the research has way more impact.
$segment3/776 // Ryan: Therefore, you should be doing a bunch of really ambitious stuff.
$segment3/777 // Buck: What are your favorite examples of really high potential ambitious bets that people aren't pursuing very much?
$segment3/778 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/779 // Ryan: So the two examples I often think about, one of them is research into how we would decode NERLYs.
$segment3/780 // Ryan: So concretely, currently models reason in chain of thought, and that's, like, broadly legible and often to solve problems.
$segment3/781 // Ryan: Like, the model would not be able to solve the problem without it being clear that it was working on that problem based on the chain of thought because it doesn't it's not good enough at doing steganographic reasoning or be too easy to detect it's doing steganography or you could prevent it in various ways.
$segment3/782 // Ryan: In the future, model architectures might shift so that models are very directly doing reasoning in, like, opaque vectors, which we do not understand and which are more analogous to model internals than tokens, maybe or maybe not, or, like, you know, English language tokens, I should say.
$segment3/783 // Ryan: And I think that it's it's, like, pretty I feel like there's some hope.
$segment3/784 // Ryan: There's some reason to think mechanistic interpretability is very hard, which is that models might be doing, like, very low level, totally insane, incomprehensible bullshit.
$segment3/785 // Ryan: And I think that basically matches my experience of what people have seen in nonalgorithmic tasks, that it's often, like, pretty like, at least the composition of things is complicated and confusing and really messy.
$segment3/786 // Ryan: But one story is like, well, maybe we can at least decode something that's analogous to high level thoughts produced by general computational machinery.
$segment3/787 // Ryan: And so in the same way that we can, like, you know, look at the chain of thought and really roughly know what the eyes are thinking, maybe even if that wasn't produced via an imitative process, we would still be able to do some sort of, like, high level thought decoding on neurales, which would allow us to understand, like, what the AI was doing at a high level in a way that had reasonably high reliability and let us answer, like, pretty useful questions like, you know, why like, what were the options it was considering?
$segment3/788 // Ryan: Why did it think these options were better than other options?
$segment3/789 // Ryan: At least in the cases where it needed to do a bunch of explicit reasoning.
$segment3/790 // Ryan: And, like, in general, an interesting property of AIs right now is I feel like they there's not many cases where when they produce something, when they, like, generate a token, it's very clear that they had to do, like, many steps of general purpose reasoning to generate that token.
$segment3/791 // Ryan: And so it might be that one of the reasons why interpretability is hard now is there's not much general purpose reasoning going on.
$segment3/792 // Ryan: But regardless, I think that it should be possible to, like it feels like it should be spiritually possible to, like, learn a decoder for general purpose reasoning in the same way that it's possible to do unsupervised translation translation work.
$segment3/793 // Ryan: And it feels like a good version of this would maybe, like, mostly mitigate my biggest concerns.
$segment3/794 // Ryan: Mhmm.
$segment3/795 // Ryan: And I don't feel like existing work is really well targeted at this.
$segment3/796 // Ryan: I think the existing work on mechanistic interpretability feels like it's sort of imagining the wrong regime and is often trying to, like, decode behaviors that were, like, drilled into the model with training rather than trying to, like, decode the results of general purpose reasoning done internally.
$segment3/797 // Ryan: Mhmm.
$segment3/798 // Ryan: And this, like, could be on a path to doing that more, like, general purpose reasoning decoding, but, like, it isn't clearly, and it feels like a very indirect route, if anything.
$segment3/799 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/800 // Ryan: Whereas I feel like a much more direct route is be like, okay.
