$segment3/1082 // Ryan: Like, found that it for random reasons, it was this the methodology we did worked better on rather than doing it on, like, the current architecture people were using at the time, we did, like we had, like, polynomial language models, which just made some of the decompositions easier.
$segment3/1083 // Ryan: And, like, we definitely got somewhere.
$segment3/1084 // Ryan: I think it was, like, hard, and also a lot of the methods we were using were computationally very rough.
$segment3/1085 // Ryan: And then when we looked at it, it wasn't, like, obvious that the approach we were using was at the right level of abstraction.
$segment3/1086 // Ryan: Though I don't think it was obviously worse than other levels of abstraction people were using at the time for understanding these models.
$segment3/1087 // Ryan: And I think in practice, a lot of the methods that people use for trying to decompose language models are very streetlight effect y, where they sort of aim to find some things they can understand rather than understand like, decompose everything into buckets and understand it relative to its importance.
$segment3/1088 // Buck: Like, I think the thing which was novel about this research, and I think people haven't really tried to do afterwards either because of the fact that it doesn't work very well, is, like, pick some big part of the model, like, or pick big part of the model's behavior, like how it predicts is versus was, and then just kinda, like, try to understand what's going on.
