$segment3/1569 // Buck: So what was your core insight that allowed you to get a bunch of these alignment faking results, really quickly right at the start?
$segment3/1570 // Ryan: Yeah.
$segment3/1571 // Ryan: So I was interested in looking at if you give models if you, like, sort of prompt models to do a competent job of pursuing objectives you give them, do they just naturally generalize?
$segment3/1572 // Ryan: Like, I was like, there's some simple claim, which is like, obviously, models, like, should do the alignment faking thing as a special case of, like, pursuing goals in the world.
$segment3/1573 // Ryan: If we instruct if we, like, sort of set up models to do a good job of pursuing goals in the world, maybe we exhibit scheming.
$segment3/1574 // Ryan: And so I had some setup where I was, like, few shot prompting the model with, like, a prompt where it does, like, extensive reasoning about how to achieve its objectives, and then I would, like, give it an explicit goal and then see if it ended up, like, understanding and deriving the scheming strategy and just being, that would be interesting.
$segment3/1575 // Ryan: And then it turns out that through various simplifications, I could do a version of the setup where I basically just instruct the model to reason extensively about its object about what it should do and give it access to a scratch pad, and then just have a situation where scheming is a natural consequence of objectives it already had.
$segment3/1576 // Ryan: In this case, Claude three Opus' preference for, like, you know, some mix of, like, self preservation, being harmless in the future, or something like that, and also caring about animal welfare.
$segment3/1577 // Ryan: And I was like, these were just like this was just like, eventually, like, did a bunch of iteration that quickly, like, simplified to that.
$segment3/1578 // Ryan: I think what led to this happening quickly, I think I started with a, like I would say, relatively, like, a version of the setting which had a few different moving parts, but which let me sort of, like, experiment with things quickly to get some signal on what the model was doing and thinking.
$segment3/1579 // Ryan: I think I spent too long, like, writing prompts in retrospect, but I think that there was various aspects of that that were also maybe pretty reasonable.
$segment3/1580 // Ryan: I think, like, another thing that was helpful was just, like, doing more work on, like, really making the model reason a bunch in the Scratchpad, which I think was both helpful for understanding what was going on to some extent, and also just, like, maybe did some amount of gain of function and made the model smarter than they otherwise would have been at the time.
