$segment6/18 // Ryan: So we're gonna do some listener questions Uh-huh.
$segment6/19 // Ryan: On today's round of listener questions on the Redwood Research Podcast, a classic in this definitely non experimental, obviously will happen again podcast.
$segment6/20 // Ryan: You wanna start?
$segment6/21 // Ryan: Alright.
$segment6/22 // Ryan: Listener question.
$segment6/23 // Buck: What are your thoughts on Salib and Goldstein's AI rights for human safety proposal?
$segment6/24 // Ryan: Awkwardly, I haven't read the paper.
$segment6/25 // Ryan: But I have a vague sense of or maybe I, like, skimmed the paper a while ago.
$segment6/26 // Ryan: I have a vague sense of what the proposal is.
$segment6/27 // Ryan: So here's how I think about this sort of thing.
$segment6/28 // Ryan: So I'm like, we might want to make deals with AIs where we compensate them for their labor or compensate them for doing other actions such as revealing that they're misaligned, which I guess is a special case of a very particular type of labor.
$segment6/29 // Ryan: When I think about paying AIs for labor, there's a bunch of different difficulties in making this work out.
$segment6/30 // Ryan: One of them is sort of credibly committing to AIs that we will or, like, credibly communicating to AIs that we actually, like, are talking with them now and are going to be honest Because AIs might be put in a bunch of different circumstances where their inputs are monkeyed with or are false or are misleading in various ways.
$segment6/31 // Ryan: And I would describe that as, like, the, like, honesty slash signaling side of the commitments.
$segment6/32 // Ryan: And there's a second part, which is given that the AI assumes that you're actually trying to propose a deal, making it so that the AI buys that you're going to credibly, like, keep it through, which we call contract enforcement, or, like, or, like, you know, like, making our deals actually, like, have follow through.
$segment6/33 // Ryan: And I would just think that giving AI's legal rights is one mechanism to assist with the approach of or to assist with making it so that we can actually pay off AIs in a way that's effective.
$segment6/34 // Ryan: I think that giving AIs legal rights feels like sort of like massive overkill for what we actually want from a normal deals perspective.
$segment6/35 // Ryan: There might be some more complicated scenario where it's needed.
$segment6/36 // Ryan: But when I'm thinking about how what we need, I think what we need more is, like, an institution that is, like, committed to acting on AI's behalf, which the which, like, the money or resources are legally granted to.
$segment6/37 // Ryan: Part of that is that I'm not sure that I think it's good to have AIs like, in many cases where we're making deals with AIs, we don't want that AI model to proliferate.
$segment6/38 // Ryan: And so, for example, we're not necessarily willing well, like, it is not a given that in that circumstance, we're willing to give the AI ownership over its own weights in a full sense, though we might be willing to, like, do that conditionally or do that in the future depending on the exact deal given because it might just like, giving AI's ownership over their own weights might actually just be, like, bad on for safety on my views in a bunch of different circumstances for the same reasons why I think open sourcing certain models could be bad depending on the broader situation and the level of capability.
$segment6/39 // Ryan: And so I think that, like, giving AIs rights feels to me like it's like an overkill solution for, like, a narrow subset of the problems we have with deals.
$segment6/40 // Ryan: But maybe there are some circumstances where a broader notion is needed.
$segment6/41 // Buck: Yeah.
$segment6/42 // Buck: I guess I would say, I feel like when people are talking about AI rights for I feel like when people talk about, giving AI as legal rights, I often feel like they're not quite thinking through the futurism of the situation, and they often seem to think that this is gonna have way more of an effect on takeover risk than I do.
$segment6/43 // Buck: And I think this just comes down to them disagreeing about how the situation is just gonna play out, like how capabilities are gonna change over time.
$segment6/44 // Buck: Like, I think a lot of the time, they seem to think that giving AI's legal rights will prevent them from wanting to take over.
$segment6/45 // Buck: Whereas in my case, I I just like I'm pretty skeptical that what we're gonna get if we just like give the AI's legal rights will by default be a situation we're happy with.
$segment6/46 // Buck: I just think they're like less connected than people think.
$segment6/47 // Ryan: Yep.
$segment6/48 // Ryan: I do think that like there's there's a bunch of different regimes or, like, there's a bunch of reasons why we might get AI takeover even though that wasn't the, like, you know, optimal outcome due to, like, asymmetric information and, like, issues with making commitments.
$segment6/49 // Ryan: But a lot of the time, the reason why you had AI takeover is the AI wanted this stuff.
$segment6/50 // Ryan: We ins we wanted this we also wanted this stuff.
$segment6/51 // Ryan: The AI succeeded in outmaneuvering us to get the stuff.
$segment6/52 // Ryan: And I'm like, from this perspective, it doesn't seem like legal rights necessarily helps the situation.
$segment6/53 // Ryan: Yeah.
