$segment6/252 // Buck: I think the simplest argument for this is like, what were you planning on doing with your monitor?
$segment6/253 // Buck: So for example, one type of thing you might wanna do with your monitor is, whenever the AI proposes an action, you run your monitor on it.
$segment6/254 // Buck: And then if it's above some threshold of sketchiness, show it to a human auditor who will evaluate this action and decide whether it was an escape attempt and shut everything down.
$segment6/255 // Buck: And, of course, the big limitation here is you don't have access to very many humans, and so you can't actually audit very many actions.
$segment6/256 // Buck: Maybe you can audit one in 10,000 or one in a thousand or something.
$segment6/257 // Buck: And a thing you can do if you wanna use your monitor without having to rely on human labor so much is just 1% of the time, like, you know, 0.01% of the time have a human look at the action.
$segment6/258 // Buck: But then 1% of the time, which is to say, like, with a lower suspiciousness threshold, just throw away the action that the untrusted model took and sample another action and then just execute that action instead.
$segment6/259 // Buck: This is an example of an improvement to a control protocol that is not at all thought of as, like, improving the quality of your monitor, but in many toy models of the situation, drastically drastically improves safety because of the fact that you now get to intervene on a 100 times as many potential attacks.
